What's in a name? That which we call a cookie by any other name would taste as sweet.
-Amanda Shakespeare
.
.
It really doesn‚Äôt take much to make me happy. This cookie...or two...or three...will do. After Thanksgiving, I told myself I wouldn‚Äôt bake again before Christmas so we didn‚Äôt have too much temptation in the house. But I forgot I hadn‚Äôt baked these traditional cookies yet. I hesitate to call them German cookies (Marmeladenpl√§tzchen) because I think the Austrians claim them as well (Linzeraugen/kekse). üòÑ
.

Regardless of the owner, they are the best cookies in the world. Sitting here by the tree with cookie in one hand and tea in the other, I am truly in my happy place.

Only two more months until baby girl is here. It‚Äôs hard to believe how fast the time has gone!
.
.
And two more weeks until I‚Äôll be in Michigan with my family for the holidays. It‚Äôs about a 12-hour drive from Connecticut, but my doctor has ordered that we stop every hour to stretch my legs. So we‚Äôll be splitting the trip up over two days so we‚Äôre not in a rush. .
.
I‚Äôm pretty sure little girl will stay warm and cozy in my belly over the holidays, but it‚Äôs still good to be prepared for anything. So I‚Äôll be packing a hospital bag for the road just in case. üòâ I know a few people who recently delivered early (both first babies), which puts me on high alert. I‚Äôll be 33 weeks when we drive to MI and 35 weeks when we drive back, so I should be okay. But still, better to be ready. üòÑ
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
Any guesses on which week our daughter will decide to make her grand entrance? Please nobody say 41 weeks. üòÖ

On the shores of New Hampshire üåä
.
.
After a busy couple days cooking and entertaining for Thanksgiving, we made a quick escape up to New Castle, NH. We stayed in a beautiful hotel called ‚ÄúWentworth by the Sea,‚Äù with views of the harbor and ocean beyond. There‚Äôs nothing like being near the water. I wish we could have stayed longer, but I was still so happy for the brief time we had up there.
.
.
The drive back home was pretty eventful though. We thought it would just take us three hours, but it ended up taking more than five because of a snowstorm. There were accidents everywhere. It always seems like for the first snowstorm of the year especially, people forget how slick the roads can be and drive too recklessly. I‚Äôm just thankful we made it home okay.
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
Did you celebrate Thanksgiving? What were you up to last weekend?

The maternity coat has made its first appearance. I tried to make my regular coat last as long as possible, but the last zip-up attempt made me realize it would no longer work. ‚ò∫Ô∏è
.
.
My husband, cousin, and I took a little trip to Boston last weekend, and as always, the city never ceases to woo me with its charms. .
.
At our first cafe stop, it was so crowded that we ended up sharing a table with two other people local to the Boston area. They were so warm and friendly, as well as hilarious. The woman in particular had a dream of writing a book on how to use Tinder in your 60s. Or more like, how NOT to use it (no posing with dead animals, no bathroom selfies, etc.) The man piped in that it should be called ‚ÄúTinder Moments.‚Äù That gives you just a little glimpse into how entertaining they were. üòÇ
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
Do you enjoy meeting new people on your travels or do you prefer to focus on the people you‚Äôre with?

Another snippet from my walk on Yale campus last weekend. üçÅ
.
.
After returning home, I decorated our Christmas tree (swipe right for pics). üéÑ I usually like to put it up before Thanksgiving, but this year it felt a little early for me. I actually felt a bit of sadness while I was putting it up...perhaps some homesickness. I almost regretted taking all the decorations out, but decided to just go ahead with it.
.
.
Sitting here now, a few days later, looking at the tree, I‚Äôm glad I put it up already. It fills my heart with joy when I get to turn the lights on after work. Somehow the tree instantly makes our home feel cozier.
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
What things make your home feel the most cozy this time of year?

.
.

I‚Äôm laying here at 7:30 p.m. wondering why I‚Äôm so stinking tired, and then I remember...oh yeah, I‚Äôm pregnant.
.
.
I try not to blame everything I feel on pregnancy, but truth is, it does a lot of weird things to your body. üòÖ I think my biggest symptom has been these moments of fatigue that will hit me all of a sudden. And sleep is starting to become more of an ordeal. Now I understand all those women who recommended sleeping with pillows under your stomach and behind your back. üò¨
.
.
But overall, pregnancy has been an enjoyable experience. I love feeling my girl kicking inside me, reminding me that she‚Äôs there...in the moments when I‚Äôm not looking at my protruding belly.
.
.
I suppose I should take advantage of my fatigue and enjoy sleeping as much as I can, because in three months, I have a feeling sleep will become a distant memory. üòÇ
.
.
‚ù•
.
.

The difference between a good day and a bad day is often just your perspective. .
.
Yesterday I had a pretty bad attitude, and in retrospect, my day could have been much better if I had chosen to see things in a more positive light. Today was much better. Not much changed except for my attitude, and that was enough.
.
.
I‚Äôve had quite a bit going on this past week, so I haven‚Äôt had much time to work on my creative projects. But this weekend I‚Äôm hoping to finish organizing the nursery/office and put up our Christmas tree (yes, I‚Äôm one of those people who puts it up way early). üéÑüíïüòÑ Looking forward to a couple #daysofsimpleandslow.
.

This was my favorite hall at Longwood Gardens. It was a gorgeous mix of green and purple. üíöüíúüíöüíú
.
.
So today I made a meal plan for the entire month of November. I usually just plan out meals for one week at a time, but this time I got ambitious and decided to plan the whole month at once. When my husband came and saw the calendar I drafted in Word, he said only someone with a German background would be that organized. üòúüòÇ I‚Äôm sure that‚Äôs not entirely true but it cracked me up when he said it. .
.
We often tease each other about our cultural backgrounds. I think that‚Äôs one of the best parts of an international marriage (though it probably goes for any marriage). You both bring unique strengths and weaknesses to the table and learn how the other can complement them.
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
How do you do your meal planning? Do you plan each day in advance or just wing it?

How do you come up with your captions?
.
.
Do you look at the picture you want to post and let it inspire you?
.
Do you have a thought running through your mind all day that you can‚Äôt wait to write out?
.
Do you sit in contemplation right before posting and just write the first thing that comes to mind?
.
.
For me, I think it could be any of these things. Sometimes the words flow immediately, and sometimes I struggle so hard to put together a coherent thought that I end up not posting at all. üòÇ .
.
Funny how Instagram has shifted from just being a space to share photos to a place where the captions beneath them are just as important, if not even more so. I don‚Äôt mind it though. I love reading people‚Äôs captions and appreciate when someone puts thought into them. .
.
‚ù•
.
.
So what‚Äôs your caption-drafting routine?

Purpose. Mindfulness. Creativity.
.
.
These are words I‚Äôve been seeing a lot in this space lately. Sometimes it feels like certain people have it all figured out. They know what they want to achieve in the world. They have the right mindset. They come up with a constant stream of creative ideas.
.
.
But it‚Äôs easy to see someone else‚Äôs success and forget the struggle they had to get there.
.
.
I‚Äôm trying to be more intentional about my goals. And I‚Äôm trying to set more mini goals that are realistic to achieve rather than just thinking of a long-term dream with no tangible steps on how to achieve it.
.
.
I‚Äôll never get anywhere if I keep dreaming and never take action. The same goes for you. üòä
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
Are you a big dreamer or do you think more practically about the here and now?

üçÅ 25 Weeks üçÅ
.
.
Our Saturday morning began with a walk in our beautiful fall wonderland. I just love this time to year, when the air is so crisp and fresh. I have the windows open now to let all the cool air refresh our apartment.
.
.
Tonight we have some guests coming over so I‚Äôll be doing a lot of cooking and cleaning. I actually love having days like this when I can just listen to podcasts and music and work with my hands at the same time. .
.
I‚Äôm reorganizing my pantry at the moment, too, trying to use a lot more glass containers and ditching the manufacturer packaging. I‚Äôll have to show a before and after when it‚Äôs done. Been totally inspired by some Pinterest pantries lately. ;)
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
What are your plans for this weekend?

Sometimes it‚Äôs hard to fathom that in less than four months, this little one inside of me will be in my arms. I‚Äôm sitting here on the couch in complete and total silence. For the last 30 years, I‚Äôve been able to control my own schedule for the most part. If I needed a night to myself, I could do it. No problem.
.
.
But soon, a tiny little human is going to call the shots for me. üòÑ No more lazy nights on the couch. Life will be a mixture of nursing, changing diapers, giving baths, and holding my little girl closely. It‚Äôs overwhelming to think about sometimes, but I know it will be beautiful.
.
.
Before I know it, she‚Äôll be 18 and pursuing whatever dream God placed on her heart. Every parent I talk to says the time goes so quickly. I want to cherish each and every moment. Yes, life will be different. I won‚Äôt be independent little me anymore. But my life will be richer, too. Much richer. üíú
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
What was one of your favorite things to do when you were a kid?

Life is short; pet a donkey.
.
.
That‚Äôs about as deep as I can get for today. You know those days when your brain has turned to mush and everything feels like a struggle? That was today. But thankful I kept it together at the grocery store and didn‚Äôt drop a jar of marinara like the other girl I saw. Poor thing. .
.
I actually had the sweetest lady come up to me at the store to say she loved my baby bump and that my skin was glowing. I almost laughed because my skin has not been feeling glowy at all. Another thing I‚Äôm thankful for: concealer. üòâ
.
.
But that ended up being my main takeaway from this day. A person can instantly lift your mood by saying something unexpectedly kind. That‚Äôs the kind of person I always want to be, even on the days when the last thing I feel like doing is talking to a random stranger. I could very well change that person‚Äôs inner dialogue for the better.
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
Have you had someone say or do something kind for you today? Or maybe you were the one who bestowed the kindness? ‚ò∫Ô∏è

I‚Äôm probably starting to sound like a broken record by mentioning the ‚ÄúLetters from a Hopeful Creative‚Äù podcast again, but there was another tidbit I recently heard from them that got me thinking a lot.
.
.
The topic was on ‚Äúfinding your niche‚Äù and how there‚Äôs so much advice out there about attracting specific types of people to your feed and making sure your content aligns with them. But they said if you focus too much on creating content for a specific audience rather than on what you want to post, you end up not fully being your authentic self.
.
.
Ultimately, the people you want following you are the ones who like YOU, not the image you portray. So don‚Äôt box yourself in for fear that you‚Äôll lose people by posting something that seems ‚Äúoff brand.‚Äù .
.
I started this feed mainly as a way to connect with fellow travelers and share photos of my adventures with people who might find them interesting, rather than spamming the people in my regular friend/family circle. The thing is, over time, I‚Äôve found myself intrigued by so many different types of feeds on here ‚Äî those dedicated to creative writing, DIY projects and interior design, language learning, simple living and sustainability, etc. I love them all in different ways, perhaps because they all tap in to a specific part of me.
.
.
So while I have a few more Santorini photos I want to share, I may also start weaving in other photos from my everyday life. Based on a recent stories poll I did, it sounds like you might not mind the expansion. ‚ò∫Ô∏è Hope you guys will still stick around, but I understand if it‚Äôs not your thing. However, travel will always be an important part of my life, so those photos won‚Äôt go away entirely!
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
What are your thoughts about finding and sticking to your niche? Do you follow accounts because they maintain a certain theme or because you‚Äôre drawn to the person as a whole?

For me a photo is kind of like a Polly Pocket. Did you ever play with those when you were little? They are these little boxes you open to display a scene, and they come with miniature dolls and accessories to make the scene come alive. See some examples in my stories. ‚ò∫Ô∏è
.
.
This Santorini sunrise photo is like a Polly Pocket for me. On a lousy day, I can look at this picture and be transported back to that scene when Oia was completely quiet and the first hints of light began peering over the caldera. It was serene and awe-inspiring at the same time. I‚Äôll never forget it.
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
Do you have a ‚ÄúPolly Pocket‚Äù moment you love to open up through a specific photo?

üçÅ In Many Hues üçÅ
.
.
Shorter days. Brisk nights. Cool breezes. Swirls of fallen leaves. Hot cups of tea. Cozy knit sweaters. Baked apple pie. Autumn. üçÇ
.
.
I remember the first time my grandparents took me to a pumpkin patch. I was in awe of the size of those peculiar orange spheres. What did they do? What were they used for? Questions I would never think to ask as an adult. .
.
When you‚Äôre a child, everything is novel and exciting. The thing you often see as commonplace becomes a child‚Äôs new favorite toy.
.
.
As I walk into motherhood, I often think about what it will be like to show my daughter all the firsts in life. The feeling of a leaf between her fingers. The sound of rain pelting on the roof. The sight of squirrels squabbling over an acorn. How exciting the life of a child is!
.
.
And how exciting to have the chance to experience all of those things with her. To be enamored by the simple things. To renew my childlike wonder. To fully experience life in its many hues.
.
.
This caption is in response to @nanhes.jungle‚Äôs creative writing challenge. #daysofsimpleandslow
. .
The prompt for this week is ‚ÄúIn Many Hues,‚Äù as part of her fall inspiration series. I have never done one of these creative writing challenges before but I‚Äôve been seeing so many lovely posts in my feed that I thought I‚Äôd give it a go. ;)
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
What simple thing has given you joy today?

There is something so satisfying to me about a creative craft or project. I think it‚Äôs especially nice if you have a desk job where you‚Äôre staring at a screen all day. Being able to work with your hands and see your vision come to life is so much fun.
.
.
If you‚Äôve been following my stories about my nursery project, you‚Äôll know I‚Äôve been creating some paper flowers for a wall display. It‚Äôs tedious work, but I just pop on a podcast and let my mind wander away, and it‚Äôs been just lovely. .
.
Tonight my husband and a friend picked up the wardrobe for the nursery, so we‚Äôll be assembling that within the next couple days. It‚Äôs all starting to come together!
.
.
Oh and to answer the question in my last post about the nursery color theme, I think most of you guessed correctly, and if you know me at all, you won‚Äôt be surprised. Purple it is. üíú‚ò∫Ô∏è But not a super bright purple. More subtle purple tones with cream, white, and black woven in. I‚Äôm really excited to see how it all turns out!
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
What has been the highlight of your day today?

Once I get started with a project, I put all my energy into it. The latest project is putting together my daughter‚Äôs nursery!
.
.
It‚Äôs been both fun and overwhelming to consider all the different options. There are so many amazing ideas out there! But slowly I‚Äôm making some decisions, and piece by piece, it‚Äôs coming together. .
.
‚ù•
.
.
Any guesses about the color theme? My stories might give a hint. üôà

Sporting a tiny baby bump in Santorini. üíï
.
.
Pregnancy is such a crazy thing. Watching your belly grow day by day, feeling a tiny human beginning to kick inside of you. I‚Äôve always heard it said that a baby changes everything. I‚Äôm sure this is completely true.
.
.
I often think about how my life will change as a mom. I wasn‚Äôt one of those girls who dreamt all the time about becoming a mom. I knew I wanted kids one day, but I was never a kid magnet. In fact, I often thought I would make a terrible mom because I didn‚Äôt feel I had that maternal side to me.
.
.
But with each passing day, I sense my love for this little girl increasing, and it gives me hope that I will be a good mom. I won‚Äôt be a perfect mom, but I‚Äôll be a loving mom. And all I can do is try my best every day to be an example that she will look up to.
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
Have you always dreamt about being a parent or do you feel you‚Äôre a late bloomer in this area (or you don‚Äôt want kids at all)?

I‚Äôve been working from home for a little over six months now. It‚Äôs had its ups and downs, which I could probably share in a detailed blog post at some point, but for now I‚Äôll just share my top pros and cons:
.
.
PRO: I love being able to sleep in a little longer in the morning and not have to rush out the door and deal with traffic and all that mayhem. .
.
CON: I miss being around people all day long. .
.
PRO: I get less interruptions at my desk which allows me to stay more focused on my work.
.
.
CON: It‚Äôs easy to have FOMO during meetings and other events when I‚Äôm the only one not there in person. A video call is just NOT the same as being face-to-face, even though it‚Äôs a huge improvement over a traditional phone call.
.
.
PRO: I love being able to cook or throw in a load of laundry during lunch...or even take a nap if I feel like it. üòÑ
.
.
CON: On the days I‚Äôm feeling super exhausted or distracted, it‚Äôs hard being alone and not having others around you to keep you on track.
.
.
PRO: In general, I feel like I can make more use of my day because I spend less time getting ready in the morning, driving to and from work, etc.
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
I‚Äôm not one of those people who will say working from home is the greatest thing ever, but it does have its perks. I‚Äôm not sure it‚Äôs how I‚Äôll always want to work, but it‚Äôs really nice to have this option during this season of my life, especially as I get ready to welcome our little one into the family.
.
.
Do you work from home or in an office? What‚Äôs your preference and why?

I‚Äôve been loving the podcast ‚ÄúLetters from a Hopeful Creative‚Äù with @me_and_orla and @jencarrington_ . So often when you listen to advice about how to pursue your creative dreams, you get a lot of basic tips on how to grow your social media following or find your niche. It honestly gets old and tiring.
.
.
This podcast keeps it real in discussing the struggles of pursuing creativity on the side of a full-time job and having a family and all the other things that can take up your time. .
.
Sometimes after a long day of work, I don‚Äôt have much more to give mentally. But creative pursuits shouldn‚Äôt feel like a chore. If you don‚Äôt have the energy, don‚Äôt force it. And don‚Äôt compare your progress with someone who is in a totally different life situation than you are. (Don‚Äôt compare yourself in general, but especially not with those whose circumstances are totally out of reach for you.) üòä
.
.
‚ù•
.
.
